subject_prompt_600:
Tudeshk Rural District

The name "Tudeshk Rural District" refers to the rural population that lives in the district. It is a district that includes Tudeshk, Krasnoyarsk, and Zhupan.

Its borders are those of Krasnoyarsk City. The borders were officially defined in 1872 but have been in dispute ever since. The dispute has recently been resolved, with the Russian Federation agreeing to the border between it and Krasnoyarsk; however, the exact borders have yet to be determined.


The area is home to many ethnic groups – Kazakhs, Tajiks, Uzbeks, Kazakhs from Urals, Uzbek Tatars, Crimean Tatars, Finns, Lithuanians, Greeks, Albanians, Turks, and Persians. Tudeshk Rural District was formerly known as Northern Kazakhstan.

In 1905, Tudeshk Rural District became part of Russia. Today, only a small number of villages remain in its boundaries. Most of them have been incorporated into other administrative units.

History of Tudeshk Rural District

After World War I, Kazakhstan, Russia and Greece established the Transcaucasian Railway (TCT) connecting Kazakhstan to western Europe via the city of Astrakhan. This railway was constructed as the sole means of economic growth in the region. The railway was completed in 1921. It consisted of three tracks, each consisting of a length of over 2,200 km. The railway was financed by the Tsarist Government and run by the Railways Corporation.

Initially, the railroad ran north-south through Western Kazakhstan. Later, a branch was built to the south.

Between 1921 and 1930, the railway was also used for transporting Soviet troops across the Caucasus Mountains. But the track was shut down in 1934 due to financial reasons (some sources say because it had to be extended due to the Great Depression). It was re-opened in 1935 after completion of the second section.

Tudeshk rural district was also part of the Transcaucasian Railway. However, starting in the 1980's, a new rail line was built on the basis of Soviet concepts. The train route included a spur running in the direction of Astana. This was opened in 1983. However, the tracks are not suitable for cars, hence only a handful of vehicles are allowed through the area.

A railway stop was added at Tukhachevsky Station in Astana from 1985 onwards. The line runs westwards along the northern edge of Zhupan. The entire route is paved, except for a small portion along the southern shore of Lake Aktobe.

The Russian government took control of the railway in 2000, although Kazakhstan maintains a minority share of ownership.

Population

The total population of the district is estimated to be 3,500,000 people.

Tudeshk District was formed in 1948 (during British Mandate) and is divided into four sub districts:

- Tudeshk Rural District (with a population of about 200 thousand)

- Tudeshk City

- Tudeshk City Rural

- Tudeshk West

Tudeshk City Rural is a separate legal entity within the district.

- a special municipality within the city, serving all residents of Tudeshk city

- city is divided in two parts - north and south, in case of conflicts between residents of each of these parts

- it includes almost 2 hundred cities, towns and villages

- it has its own police force, fire service, and local institutions with their own budgets and staff

This is also another unique characteristic of Tudeshk District – it's largest industry is agriculture.

There are several farms located near the district, like in a forested area. These farms have many varieties of vegetables, fruits and vegetables produce. As you can see on this picture, the vegetables here can be used for everyday food or for cooking in Tudeshk Restaurant in the city.

Here is a short video showing Tudeshk District. You can watch all the videos here.

Tudeshk City is where most of the businesses are located. It's important to note that Tudeshk City Rural is considered a city as well. It's called "City" because it's not only a place, but a real city. The people are living there and working there together.

Here is some info regarding Tudeshk City:

- a big city

- its main industries are manufacturing and business-related

- it's known internationally for its high level of education

- it has its own military and police force

- it has a population of around 40 thousand

It is one of the five official cities in the city – it's the only city that isn't at the center of its district. And yet it has been officially designated by UNESCO as a World Heritage site in 1990.

You can also read more about Tudeshk City here.

Tudeshk City Rural is located in the southern part of Tudeshk district, near the water-filled Lake Tajik.

With its wide open space, you can enjoy walks with your family. I recommend taking a bike along the riverbanks of the lake. There are also many other green areas that can provide pleasant restful moments.
